What you want is not “another app.”

You want the extraction layer that sits underneath many apps.

Not Tinder.
Not Pokémon cards.
Not shopping.
Not ranking movies.

The thing beneath all of them:

a preference-intelligence engine that turns repeated choices plus context into structured human signal.

That is the real asset.

Core idea

Every app where a person picks between options is secretly generating:
	•	preference data
	•	hesitation data
	•	context data
	•	identity data
	•	tradeoff data
	•	drift-over-time data

The primitive is simple:

A vs B under context C, chosen by person P at time T.

That single event is far more valuable than a like button, because it reveals:
	•	what they preferred
	•	what they rejected
	•	what they compared against
	•	how strong the choice was
	•	what conditions shaped it

That means the engine should not be built around “profiles” first.

It should be built around comparison events.

