What the engine actually learns

Not just “this user likes X.”

It learns at least six layers.

1. Surface preference

Direct choices.

Example:
	•	user tends to choose profile archetype A over B
	•	user tends to prefer card art style X over Y

2. Relative tradeoff weights

What someone sacrifices to get something else.

Example:
	•	prefers humor over beauty when forced
	•	prefers stability over novelty
	•	prefers rarity over nostalgia
	•	prefers symmetry over aggression in design

This is where real value starts.

3. Latent taste vector

A hidden multi-dimensional representation of preference.

Example dimensions:
	•	novelty seeking
	•	status orientation
	•	warmth sensitivity
	•	aesthetic complexity tolerance
	•	risk appetite
	•	preference consistency
	•	tribal affinity
	•	gendered signaling response
	•	dominance/submission cue response
	•	nostalgia bias

These are not entered manually.
They are inferred.

4. Context modulation

Preferences are not static.

Example:
	•	at night user prefers bolder choices
	•	when fatigued user chooses familiar options
	•	after losses user prefers safer picks
	•	in group settings user chooses more status-signaling options

5. Identity drift

How preferences change over time.

Example:
	•	short-term mood swing vs long-term taste evolution
	•	post-breakup selection patterns
	•	seasonal drift
	•	self-image change

6. Predictive behavior

What they are likely to choose next, buy next, click next, desire next, reject next.

That’s where monetization and strategy emerge.

