The algorithmic stack

Here is the real architecture.

Layer 1: Event normalization

All incoming actions get translated into a canonical format.

Different app actions become a common language:
	•	Tinder swipe right → weak positive preference
	•	Tinder super like → strong positive preference
	•	pause then swipe left → conflicted rejection
	•	Pokémon A chosen over B → pairwise positive
	•	revisit saved item → delayed positive
	•	purchase after comparison → revealed strong preference

Normalize all of them into:

(user, item_a, item_b, action, strength, time, context, outcome)


⸻

Layer 2: Feature extraction

You need features from both the user side and the item side.

Item features
	•	structured metadata
	•	text embeddings
	•	image embeddings
	•	handcrafted tags
	•	price/status/rarity
	•	style clusters

User state features
	•	prior session behavior
	•	long-term latent vector
	•	recent mood proxy
	•	activity rhythm
	•	consistency score
	•	novelty score

Interaction features

These are crucial.

Not just “is item attractive?”
But:
	•	item’s trait X interacts strongly with user’s trait Y
	•	contrast effect between A and B
	•	choice depends on matchup, not absolute value

That means you should model comparisons, not just isolated items.

⸻

Layer 3: Pairwise ranking model

This is the heart.

You want a model that predicts:

probability that user U chooses item A over item B in context C

Base form:

P(A > B | U, C) = sigmoid(S(U, A, C) - S(U, B, C))

Where:
	•	S(U, A, C) = score of item A for user U in context C

This score can be built from:

S(U, A, C) = user_vector · item_vector + context_effect + interaction_terms

That gives you:
	•	personalization
	•	context sensitivity
	•	tradeoff reasoning

Good starter models
	•	Bradley-Terry model
	•	Elo-style updating
	•	Bayesian preference learning
	•	factorization machines
	•	gradient boosted trees over pairwise deltas
	•	deep two-tower or three-tower ranking models

Best practical path

Start simple:
	1.	Bradley-Terry / Elo for pairwise core
	2.	add context features
	3.	add embeddings
	4.	add latent factor decomposition
	5.	add sequential modeling later

⸻

The important insight:

choices are not independent

Human preference is sequence-sensitive.

What they saw right before changes what they choose now.

So you need a sequence layer.

⸻

Layer 4: Sequence modeling

Track order effects:
	•	contrast effects
	•	fatigue
	•	escalation
	•	boredom
	•	satiation
	•	recency bias
	•	rebound behavior

Example:
	•	after seeing 10 highly polished profiles, a more “real” profile can overperform
	•	after a streak of rejection, standards may relax or harden
	•	after high novelty, people often swing back to familiarity

Useful features:
	•	rolling accept rate
	•	rolling novelty average
	•	recent emotional proxy
	•	time since last reward
	•	streak counts
	•	category exposure saturation

You can model this with:
	•	handcrafted rolling stats first
	•	then RNN / Transformer sequence model later if needed

