A good mathematical core

Here’s a compact version.

Step 1: pairwise score

s(u, i, c) = b_i + p_u^T q_i + w^T c + \phi(u,i,c)

Where:
	•	b_i = item baseline
	•	p_u = user latent vector
	•	q_i = item latent vector
	•	c = context feature vector
	•	phi(u,i,c) = learned interaction function

Step 2: preference probability

P(i \succ j | u,c) = \sigma(s(u,i,c) - s(u,j,c))

Step 3: online update

Each new event updates:
	•	user vector
	•	item vectors
	•	confidence estimates
	•	drift estimates

Step 4: uncertainty-aware inference

Track confidence intervals so the system knows:
	•	stable preferences
	•	weak guesses
	•	temporary noise
	•	contradictory behavior

That part matters a lot. Otherwise the engine becomes overconfident nonsense.

⸻

You also need a confidence model

Not all data points are equally meaningful.

A good engine weights events by evidence quality.

Event quality score

Use factors like:
	•	decision time
	•	repeated consistency
	•	accidental-tap likelihood
	•	option similarity
	•	session fatigue
	•	post-choice follow-through

Example:
fast accidental swipe with no later engagement = low weight

slow deliberate selection followed by revisit/purchase/match = high weight

So each event should carry:

weight = f(confidence, dwell, follow_through, repetition, noise_penalty)

Then training uses weighted events.

⸻

The biggest mistake to avoid

Do not confuse:
	•	correlation
with
	•	stable trait
or
	•	causal mechanism

Example:
someone picking rugged-looking people at 1 a.m. does not mean “rugged is their core type.”
It may mean:
	•	fatigue
	•	temporary mood
	•	sequence effect
	•	presentation bias
	•	current social context

So the engine needs to separate:

stable signal

long-term identity tendencies

contextual signal

temporary state

platform signal

what the interface itself induced

adversarial signal

bots, gaming, fake behavior

That separation is what makes your tool valuable.

